Durban - Police recovered dangerous weapons and arrested three people during a raid at the Dalton Beer Hall in uMbilo on Friday morning. An informal settlement has mushroomed within the walls of the Beer Hall. Young children could be seen walking around while police searched the shacks for drugs and weapons. Outside, piles of dirt and pools of water filled the space between more shacks that have been erected.  To view this video please enable JavaScript, and consider upgrading to a web browser that
    supports HTML5 video This is a modal window. Beginning of dialog window. Escape will cancel and close the window. End of dialog window. The raid, part of Operation Fiyela 2, was effectively carried out by members of the uMbilo police station along with specialised SAPS units, Metro Police and the Department of Home Affairs. Lieutenant Colonel Stanley Perumal, uMbilo SAPS Visible Policing Commander, said the men were charged for drug dealing, being in possession of suspected stolen items and dealing in liquor without a licence respectively. “We recovered one unlicensed firearm and ammunition, three knives, a black Toyota Yaris, which we believe was stolen and drugs with an estimated street value of R10 000,”  he said. Perumal said he was proud of the results yielded by the operation and is only the start of more operations and raids planned for the area. “We are committed to ensuring that our community, both residential or businesses, are safe. This is an ongoing project,” Perumal said. Twenty-one people had their fingerprints taken using the Max ID machine. Daily News